INSERT INTO `cities` (`id`, `name`, `description`, `attitude`, `has_beach`, `population`, `area`, `altitude`, `tourism_rating`, `timezone`, `region_id`) VALUES
(1, 'Tangier', 'In the north of Morocco, on the coasts of Tangier where the Mediterranean and Atlantic waters converge, you’ll discover a unique city bearing a multicultural heritage.\n\nStroll the streets of « the White »Tangier, they are lined with lime-coated houses. Just like Delacroix or Matisse did their upon arrival, let yourself be carried away by the dreamy atmosphere that covers the city. At the foot of the high walls of the \"Kasbah\", roam through the alleys of the great \"Socco\", and admire the fortress that dominates the medina. A little far away, explore the \"Sultan\'s Palace\" which is nowaydays dedicated to the arts of Morocco. Tangier is alsos renowned for the Spanish influence on its culture, starting with the arena that stands on the \"Plaza de Torros\", not to mention the \"Cervantes\" theatre built in 1913.', 'coastal', 1, 947952, 117, 0, 4.5, 'GMT+1', 1),
(2, 'Tétouan', 'Just like its first cousin, Tangier, Tetouan boasts a peaceful atmosphere. Known as the daughter of \"Granada\", it’s a city with Hispano-Moorish footmarks. Its medina is listed as a World Heritage Site by UNESCO.\n\nNot far from Tetouan, the seaside resort of \"Tamouda Bay\" expands on fifteen kilometres of fine sandy bay. Prestigious establishments have settled there, giving a luxury setting to the region. In the cristal-clear blue waters of the Mediterranean, you can onlye enjoy a peaceful stay while getting to know the art of living of the inhabitants.\n\nThe city of Tetouan, with its multicultural identity, offers a journey through time !', 'coastal', 1, 380787, 102, 0, 4.2, 'GMT+1', 1),
(3, 'Fès', 'Fez has a special atmosphere. This 13th-century city is an imperial city of long-lasting multicultural history, that reserves unexpected surprises for its visitors.\n\nCross the walls of the famous medina of Fez, recognized by UNESCO as an outstanding universal value. Stroll through the streets of the Fez-El-Bali district. The Bab Boujloud is the easiest way to enter the medina.\n\nIn early May, the squares and alleys resound with world music, where the Festival of World Sacred Music is held in the former imperial capital, which occurs along with Jazz in Riads, one of the main events in the city\'s cultural calendar. Don\'t leave without having tasted the city\'s gastronomy, reputed to be one of the best in the world.', 'historical', 0, 1112072, 130, 400, 4.9, 'GMT+1', 3),
(4, 'Meknès', 'The Medina of Meknes and the remains of the royal palace have earned it an undisputable place on the UNESCO World Heritage List.\n\nOn El Hedime square, Bab Mansour, one of the masterpieces of Hispano-Moorish art, is the gateway to the medina. Don’t miss visiting the royal stables and granaries of Sultan Moulay Ismail.\n\nIn the North of Meknes, stands the largest Roman archaeological site in Morocco, which is Volubilis. Triumphal arch, capitol, house of Bacchus, everything bears witness to the splendour of the city and to its economic and political weight.\n\nBeing an imperial and eternal citiy, Meknes offers you the experience of a timeless stay full of heritage discovery.', 'historical', 0, 632079, 98, 500, 4.3, 'GMT+1', 3),
(5, 'Rabat', 'Rabat is a cultural city deep-rooted in history. Many masterpieces decorate its streets and squares. Visit the Kasbah des Oudayas which is a majestic and splendid architecture embellished by the surrounding gardens. Not far from the walls, stand the imposing walls of the Chellah ; a necropolis from the time of the Merinids. Crossing the walls is like entering another world ; walk among ancient vestiges, gardens and storks.\n\nRabat is also a modern eco-responsible capital with its green spaces. Beautiful parks await you, such as the botanical test garden or the Exotic Gardens of Bouknadel which is a few kilometres from the city. Rabat boasts an outstanding coastline ; on the Atlantic Ocean shores, it has kilometres of well equipped beaches that lead to the neighbouring city of Casablanca.\n\nWith its modern infrastructures and various festivals, Rabat is a living city. Airport, tram, shopping centres, cafés and restaurants, all the amenities are within your reach. Revel in bustling vibes of music that Rabat celebrates like no other city ; from Mawazine, to Jazz au Chellah and many others that fill the atmosphere with sounds and rhythms from all over the world !\n\nRabat is a city where the treasures of the past blend with the most modern and environmentally friendly achievements. ', 'historical', 1, 577827, 117, 0, 4.8, 'GMT+1', 4),
(6, 'Casablanca', 'Beautiful palm trees lining its paths, with the Atlantic ocean over the horizon, and large business buildings in every corner : Casablanca is the economic lung of Morocco ; a bustling metropolis.\n\nModern infrastructures are in the middle of charming districts, between Arab-Muslim heritage and legacies of the colonial period. Discover all the possibilities : take a stroll in the medina, which is one of latest medinas built in Morocco, roam through the centre and its art-deco buildings, and join the Hassan II mosque ; the splendid of architecture built on the water.\n\nLet yourself be tempted by the festive side of the city. Take advantage of the cornice, its clubs and festivals too, such as the Casablanca Festival, Jazzablanca or Tremplin L\'Boulevard.\n\nThe coastline, bordered by beaches equipped to suit all your comfort, invites you to experience the most fun activities that will make your stay more enjoyable, from diving, to jet-skiing to boating.\n\nThe White city, Casablanca, is where culture and serenity activities blend seamlessly.', 'urban', 1, 3359818, 220, 0, 4.7, 'GMT+1', 6),
(7, 'Marrakech', 'Between tradition and modernity, Marrakech is the promise of unequalled sensations. Strolling the Jemaa El-Fna square and the souks with their shimmering colours and oriental smells, the red city offers you a complete change of scenery. Horse-drawn carriage rides, sunny terraces, travelling artists and other day and night activities will give a tates of wishful comeback.\n\nYou will be able to admire all the architectural richness of the Medina, upon visiting one of its many riads, small oriental palaces overlooking a beautiful patio. You can also relax and recharge at the Menara, a vast garden with an emblematic basin. Marrakech shower its visitors by its splendour and its diversity, you just have to leave the ramparts to be immersed in modern Morocco. The districts of Gueliz and Hivernage offer the most modern infrastructures, luxury boutiques and international ready-to-wear stores, airy avenues ; which all contribute to Marrakech\'s unique offering.\n\nBeing a growing economic bustling city, Marrakech has special festive and cultural places, such as the « Palais des Congres » and the splendid Royal Theater. Enjoy Marrakech at night by discovering the many themed venues, trendy clubs and traditional evenings that reflect the lively part of the city.\n\nIn 2016, Marrakech will host the Cop22 to help adress climate change issues, as a recognition of its new international stature and its considerable reception capacity.', 'historical', 0, 928850, 118, 0, 5, 'GMT+1', 7),
(8, 'Agadir', 'In the west of the country, bordered by the waves of the Atlantic, Agadir is one of the pearls of Morocco. Whatever the season, the sun pours its rays and the city enjoys a pleasant climate that the trade winds still soften. Above all, its 10-kilometre-long seafront offers tourists magnificent views of the blue ocean and the opportunity to laze around in the best conditions.\n\nThe main seaside resort of the country, the city with 300 days of sunshine per year, is full of activities. At the water\'s edge, cafés and restaurants open their doors to you, introduce you to the local gastronomy and submit their specialities to the enlightened judgements of your taste buds!\n\nFurther on in the city, the El Had souk spreads out through the streets, deploys its stalls: more than 6,000 shops offer themselves to your curiosity and you will enjoy strolling in this atmosphere animated by the negotiations of the merchants. Never sleepy, the city welcomes every summer the Timitar festival dedicated to world music and more specifically to Amazigh music.\n\nOpen to the ocean and the world, Agadir is an active city where it is good to relax.', 'coastal', 1, 421844, 85, 0, 4.6, 'GMT+1', 9),
(9, 'Oujda', 'Oujda, the capital of the Oriental region of Morocco, is a vibrant city steeped in history and culture. Situated near the Algerian border, it has long been a crossroads of trade and cultural exchange, making it a melting pot of diverse influences.\n\nThe city boasts a rich heritage, with a medina that showcases stunning architecture, including the historic Grand Mosque and the ancient city walls. Strolling through its bustling souks, visitors can immerse themselves in the local atmosphere, where traditional crafts, spices, and textiles abound.\n\nOujda is also known for its lush gardens and parks, providing a serene escape within the urban landscape. The nearby Beni Snassen Mountains offer breathtaking views and outdoor activities, making it an ideal destination for nature lovers and adventurers alike.', 'flat', 0, 500000, 100, 500, 3.8, 'GMT+1', 2),
(10, 'Taroudant', 'Taroudant with its majestic ramparts, is one of the most beautiful towns in Morocco. Stroll in the shade of its walls full of history and whose towers have stood for more than five centuries to protect the ancient capital from the Saadian sultans. All day long, the sun strikes these high stone columns and bathes the city in a light where the gold of its rays blends well with the ochre of the walls.\n\nCity of deep-rooted and long-standing history, Taroudant has a lot of stories to tell. Here, the dynamic of modern life blend seamlessly with the traditional heritage. Venture into the middle of its active souks alleys, negotiate with the merchants  on the stalls, and discover all the richness of local craftsmanship. Leather is particularly famous, as well as terracotta trinkets and Amazigh jewellery.\n\nTaroudant has also made a specialty, argan oil. If you want to meet specialists of this delight, go outside the ramparts, and visit cooperatives and private individuals who shell the nuts, press them, extract the substantial marrow, and then make whole oils ready to taste.\n\nIn addition to all of these assets, Taroudant is the starting point of many hikes. Located in the center of the two Atlas mountains, it benefits from an advantageous position where hikers and backpackers come in droves.\n\nNature and culture, modernity and tradition, Taroudant is definitely not lacking of attractions. Roam through its streets, criss-cross its surroundings and paint your stay with the colors of Morocco.', 'flat', 0, 200000, 250, 200, 4.1, 'GMT+1', 9),
(11, 'Errachidia', 'Nestled in the eastern part of Morocco, Errachidia is a city rich in history and natural beauty. As the capital of the Errachidia Province, it serves as a vital hub for travelers venturing into the Sahara Desert. Surrounded by stunning landscapes, including the majestic Ziz Valley and the towering Atlas Mountains, Errachidia offers a unique blend of cultural heritage and breathtaking scenery.\n\nHistorically significant, Errachidia has been influenced by various cultures, from Berber to Arab traditions, which is reflected in its architecture, local cuisine, and vibrant markets. The city is renowned for its hospitable atmosphere, where visitors can immerse themselves in the local way of life and explore traditional crafts.\n\nErrachidia also serves as a launching point for adventures into the Sahara, with opportunities for trekking, camel riding, and exploring the magnificent dunes of Merzouga. The nearby Ziz River adds to the region’s charm, creating lush oases that contrast beautifully with the arid desert landscape.', 'mountainous', 0, 120000, 350, 1000, 3.9, 'GMT+1', 8),
(12, 'Al Hoceima', 'Blue waters of the Mediterranean, its gentle, light waves and the coastline that outlines the contours of one of Morocco\'s most beautiful bays, welcome to the wonderful Al Hoceima ! The place looks like an earthly paradise. On one of its many beaches, you can relax on a deckchair, enjoy the sun during a farniente stay.\n\nAl Hoceima is not only a simple seaside town. Its surroundings has a a lots of treasures that adventure lovers come in droves to explore. Outside the town, near the fishing village of Torres de Alcala, are the ruins of five watchtowers. The Portuguese had built them during their colony. Today, the site offers pleasant walks for all lovers of old stones !\n\nInside of the city, the port is not to be overlooked. Its edges are animated by the activity of fishermen and it is lovely to stroll there. A little far away, the Moro Viejo cornice offers a magnificent sight, and its bay gives a breathtaking view of the surroundings.  ', 'coastal', 1, 150000, 150, 100, 4.5, 'GMT+1', 1),
(13, 'Khenifra', 'Khenifra, nestled in the heart of the Middle Atlas region of Morocco, is a charming city known for its stunning landscapes and rich cultural heritage. Surrounded by lush forests, rolling hills, and picturesque rivers, Khenifra serves as an ideal base for nature enthusiasts and adventure seekers.\n\nHistorically significant, Khenifra has been influenced by Berber culture, which is reflected in its traditional architecture and local customs. The city is home to vibrant markets where visitors can discover handmade crafts, aromatic spices, and authentic Moroccan cuisine, offering a true taste of the region.\n\nKhenifra is also famous for its proximity to the beautiful Michlifen Ski Resort, attracting winter sports enthusiasts during the snowy months, as well as hiking and trekking opportunities in the summer. The nearby Oum Er-Rbia River is perfect for outdoor activities like rafting and fishing, providing a serene escape into nature.', 'mountainous', 0, 90000, 200, 1200, 4.2, 'GMT+1', 5),
(14, 'Settat', 'Settat, located in the heart of Morocco, is a dynamic city that beautifully balances tradition and modernity. Known for its strategic location between Casablanca and Marrakech, Settat serves as an important economic and cultural hub.\n\nThe city boasts a rich history, with roots that trace back to ancient times. Its medina is a charming maze of narrow streets lined with traditional shops and bustling markets, where visitors can experience the vibrant local culture and sample delicious Moroccan cuisine. Key landmarks, such as the historic kasbah and various mosques, showcase the architectural heritage of the region.\n\nSettat is also surrounded by fertile plains and picturesque landscapes, making it ideal for agricultural pursuits. The nearby Oum Er-Rbia River adds to the region’s natural beauty and offers opportunities for outdoor activities.', 'flat', 0, 180000, 300, 400, 3.6, 'GMT+1', 6),
(15, 'Nador', 'Nador, located in northeastern Morocco, is a vibrant coastal city known for its stunning Mediterranean beaches and rich cultural heritage. Nestled along the shores of the Alboran Sea, Nador offers breathtaking views and a lively atmosphere, making it a popular destination for both locals and tourists.\n\nThe city is characterized by its unique blend of Moroccan and Andalusian influences, evident in its architecture, cuisine, and vibrant markets. Visitors can explore the bustling souks, where colorful textiles, handmade crafts, and aromatic spices create a feast for the senses.\n\nNador is also renowned for its natural beauty, with nearby beaches like Ras El Ma and Mar Chica offering serene spots for relaxation and water sports. The surrounding Rif Mountains provide opportunities for hiking and exploring picturesque landscapes, showcasing the region\'s diverse flora and fauna.', 'coastal', 1, 170000, 120, 50, 4.3, 'GMT+1', 2),
(16, 'Azilal', 'Azilal, a charming town nestled in the heart of the Atlas Mountains, is known for its stunning natural landscapes and rich cultural heritage. Surrounded by majestic peaks and lush valleys, Azilal serves as a perfect base for outdoor enthusiasts seeking adventure and exploration.\n\nThe town is famous for its vibrant Berber culture, which is reflected in its traditional architecture, local crafts, and warm hospitality. Visitors can explore the bustling markets, where artisans showcase handmade products, including colorful carpets and pottery, offering a glimpse into the region’s artistic traditions.\n\nAzilal is also renowned for its breathtaking natural attractions, such as the stunning Ouzoud Waterfalls, one of Morocco\'s most famous waterfalls. The surrounding countryside is ideal for hiking, trekking, and discovering the region\'s diverse flora and fauna.', 'mountainous', 0, 80000, 500, 1600, 4, 'GMT+1', 5),
(17, 'Berkane', 'Berkane, a picturesque city located in northeastern Morocco, is celebrated for its stunning landscapes, fertile agriculture, and vibrant culture. Nestled between the Mediterranean coastline and the majestic Rif Mountains, Berkane is known as the \"City of Citrus\" due to its thriving orchards and abundant fruit production, particularly oranges and lemons.\n\nThe city boasts a rich history that reflects a blend of Berber and Arab influences, evident in its traditional architecture and lively markets. Strolling through the bustling souks, visitors can immerse themselves in local life, discovering handcrafted goods, spices, and delicious street food that showcase the region\'s culinary heritage.\n\nBerkane is also a gateway to natural beauty, with nearby attractions such as the serene beaches of Saidia and the breathtaking landscapes of the Rif Mountains. Outdoor enthusiasts can enjoy a variety of activities, from hiking and mountain biking to exploring the stunning coastal scenery.', 'flat', 0, 90000, 250, 300, 3.7, 'GMT+1', 2),
(18, 'Essaouira', 'Crenellated walls, special wind, houses with white and blue facades, Essaouira, the ancient Mogador is the \"Bride of the Atlantic\".\n\nIt is one of those coastal cities where the unique atmosphere and water activities seamlessly blend. Walk quietly in the shade of its ramparts, the very ones that draw the contours of Astapor, the red city of the \"Game of Thrones\" series. Climb these walls and take the parapet walk, from where you can see the Purpuraires Islands, falcons, gulls and seagulls hovering above this nature reserve. On the other side, surfers, windsurfers and kitesurfers are taming the waves, taking advantage from the wind.\n\nA walk can lead you to the fishing port where the sailors are active. Get to the fish market where to taste the fish and seafood caught during the night. In the centre of the city, the medina invites you on a discovery wander into its winding alley. Ranked as the most beautiful cities in Morocco by Unesco, the city hums to the beat of music every summer : the Gnaoua festival celebrates Afro-Maghrebin rhythms making people’s stays memorable ones.\n\nFor several years now, Morocco has adopted a responsible tourism ; the eco-resort Mogador, which is an unmissable place to have peaceful moments, as well as the beaches of the surroundings labeled Blue Flag, are living proofs to this ambition.\n\nSpend some time there, find complete mindfullness and serenety, in this enchanting destination that makes all your dreams come true ! ', 'Coastal', 1, 78000, 160, 10, 4.5, 'GMT', 7),
(19, 'Ouarzazate', 'Ouarzazate, often referred to as the \"Hollywood of Morocco,\" is a captivating city located at the edge of the Sahara Desert. Renowned for its stunning landscapes and historical significance, Ouarzazate is a popular destination for filmmakers and travelers alike, boasting a unique blend of cultural heritage and natural beauty.\n\nThe city is home to the famous Atlas Studios, one of the largest film studios in the world, where iconic films like Gladiator and Game of Thrones were shot. Visitors can explore the studios and learn about the filmmaking process, immersing themselves in the magic of cinema.\n\nOuarzazate is also famous for its impressive kasbahs, particularly the UNESCO World Heritage site of Aït Benhaddou. This ancient fortified village, with its striking mud-brick architecture, serves as a stunning backdrop against the dramatic desert landscape and offers a glimpse into Morocco’s rich history.', 'Desert', 0, 35000, 40, 1136, 4, 'GMT', 8),
(20, 'Agdz', 'Agdz, a serene town located in the heart of the Draa Valley in southern Morocco, is a hidden gem known for its lush palm groves and stunning landscapes. Situated along the banks of the Draa River, Agdz offers a tranquil escape surrounded by the breathtaking Atlas Mountains and the vast Sahara Desert.\n\nThe town is steeped in history, with ancient kasbahs and traditional mud-brick architecture that reflect its rich cultural heritage. One of the highlights is the impressive Kasbah of Agdz, which offers panoramic views of the valley and the surrounding desert, providing a glimpse into the region\'s storied past.\n\nAgdz is also famous for its vibrant souks, where visitors can explore local crafts, spices, and traditional Moroccan goods. The warm hospitality of the residents adds to the inviting atmosphere, making it an ideal place to experience authentic Moroccan culture.', 'Rural', 0, 10000, 90, 890, 3.8, 'GMT', 8),
(21, 'Tinerhir', 'Tinerhir, a captivating town nestled in the heart of the Atlas Mountains, is renowned for its stunning natural landscapes and rich cultural heritage. Surrounded by lush palm groves and dramatic mountain scenery, Tinerhir serves as a gateway to one of Morocco’s most breathtaking natural wonders: the Todra Gorge.\n\nThe Todra Gorge, with its towering limestone cliffs and crystal-clear river, attracts outdoor enthusiasts and adventurers from around the world. Hiking, rock climbing, and exploring the gorge’s stunning pathways provide unforgettable experiences in a truly magnificent setting.\n\nTinerhir itself boasts a rich history and vibrant local culture, characterized by its traditional mud-brick architecture and bustling markets. The town’s vibrant souks are filled with local crafts, spices, and delicious Moroccan cuisine, offering a taste of the region’s culinary delights.', 'Mountainous', 0, 20000, 30, 1100, 4.2, 'GMT', 8),
(22, 'Taza', 'Taza, a vibrant city situated in northeastern Morocco, is known for its rich history, stunning landscapes, and strategic location between the Rif and Atlas Mountains. As a historical crossroads, Taza has long been a melting pot of cultures, with influences from Berber, Arab, and Spanish traditions evident throughout the city.\n\nThe city’s medina, with its narrow winding streets, is a treasure trove of traditional architecture and bustling markets. Visitors can explore local shops, where artisans sell crafts, textiles, and spices, immersing themselves in the lively atmosphere of everyday Moroccan life.\n\nOne of Taza’s notable landmarks is the historic Taza Fortress, perched on a hill overlooking the city. This ancient kasbah offers panoramic views of the surrounding valleys and mountains, providing insight into the city’s strategic importance throughout history.', 'mountainous', 0, 120000, 400, 800, 4.1, 'GMT', 3),
(23, 'Ifrane', 'With its clean air, scrubbed streets, red-roofed houses, white winters, and being set high up in Atlas mountains, Ifrane is a go-to destination !\n\nSet at an altitude of 1,650 metres, Ifrane charms never ceases to amaze its visitors with its calm waves of its lakes, and the waterfalls pouring cold waters into the valleys. It is beautifully surrounded by the largest cedar forest in the world, with its picturesque green trees on the Middle Atlas Mountains slopes.\n\nIts picturesque lake studded-parks gives its visitors a taste of an unexpected atmosphere, where its enjoyable to stroll.\n\nA rich and varied fauna decorate the most beautiful hiking trails. Diverse bird and monkey species inhabit its park : A Barbary macaque will amuse you, while you’ll get to see also the Barbary deer watching you a few meters away.\n\nIfrane is also a heritage. You’ll come to the cleanest streets in the world, and discover a typical regional craft. You’ll come across upholsterers working on their carpets, and mat makers weaving rush stems, and a pottery or Thuya wood shop where you’ll find charming knick-knacks.\n\nFrom a luxury hotel to a charming red-roofed house, this year-round destination promises you the sun and the moon !', 'mountainous', 0, 15553, NULL, 1650, 4.7, 'GMT+1', 3),
(24, 'Azrou', 'Nestled in the Middle Atlas region of Morocco, Azrou is a picturesque town renowned for its stunning landscapes, rich culture, and vibrant local life. Surrounded by lush cedar forests, Azrou is a gateway to outdoor adventures and offers a serene escape from the bustling cities.\n\nOne of Azrou’s most notable features is the Cedar Forest of Ifrane, home to the famous Barbary macaques. Visitors can explore hiking trails that meander through the majestic cedar trees, making it a perfect spot for nature lovers and wildlife enthusiasts. The tranquil environment invites picnics and leisurely strolls, providing a refreshing experience amid nature.\n\nAzrou\'s charming medina features traditional Moroccan architecture, with bustling markets and local artisans showcasing their crafts. Visitors can wander through the vibrant souks, where they can find handmade pottery, carpets, and wooden crafts, all while absorbing the lively atmosphere and engaging with friendly locals.\n\nThe town is also known for its delicious cuisine, offering a variety of traditional Moroccan dishes. Dining in local restaurants allows visitors to savor authentic flavors, from tagines to aromatic couscous, often accompanied by refreshing mint tea.\n\nFor those interested in history, Azrou boasts several cultural landmarks, including the Grand Mosque, which reflects the town’s architectural heritage. Nearby, the ancient ruins of the Roman site of Volubilis and the historic town of Meknes are easily accessible for day trips.\n\nThroughout the year, Azrou hosts various festivals that celebrate local traditions and culture, providing visitors with an opportunity to experience the town\'s vibrant community life. From music and dance to handicraft exhibitions, these events showcase the richness of Moroccan heritage.\n\nWith its blend of natural beauty, cultural richness, and warm hospitality, Azrou is a captivating destination for travelers looking to immerse themselves in the authentic Moroccan experience. Whether exploring the surrounding forests or indulging in local delicacies, Azrou promises unforgettable memories.', 'mountainous', 0, 30000, 34, 1300, 4.3, 'GMT+1', 3),
(25, 'El Jadida', 'El Jadida, a coastal gem on Morocco’s Atlantic coast, is renowned for its rich history and stunning architecture. Originally founded as a Portuguese fortress in the 16th century, the town is a UNESCO World Heritage site, offering visitors a unique blend of cultural heritage and seaside charm.\n\nOne of the most striking features of El Jadida is its well-preserved citadel, the Mazagao, which showcases a mix of Portuguese and Moroccan architectural styles. Visitors can stroll along the fortified walls, enjoying breathtaking views of the ocean and the vibrant landscape. The town’s narrow streets are lined with charming whitewashed buildings adorned with colorful tiles, creating a picturesque atmosphere.\n\nThe Cistern is another highlight, an underground water reservoir known for its remarkable architecture and beautiful light reflections. This hidden gem provides a cool respite from the sun and a fascinating glimpse into the town\'s historical significance.\n\nEl Jadida is also famous for its beautiful beaches, such as Plage de El Jadida, where visitors can relax, swim, or engage in water sports. The sandy shores are perfect for sunbathing, and the nearby beach clubs offer a lively atmosphere with cafes and entertainment.\n\nCulinary experiences abound in El Jadida, with a variety of restaurants serving delicious Moroccan dishes and fresh seafood. Dining by the sea while watching the sunset is a must-do, as the local cuisine features flavors that reflect the region’s rich maritime heritage.\n\nCulturally, El Jadida hosts various festivals throughout the year, celebrating music, art, and local traditions. These events provide an opportunity for visitors to immerse themselves in the vibrant community life and experience the warmth of Moroccan hospitality.\n\nWith its historical landmarks, beautiful beaches, and rich cultural scene, El Jadida is a captivating destination that promises a memorable experience for travelers seeking to explore the beauty and history of Morocco.', 'coastal', 1, 200000, 60, 0, 4.5, 'GMT+1', 6),
(26, 'Ksar el Kebir', 'Ksar el Kebir, is a vibrant town located in northern Morocco, close to the Atlantic coast and the historic city of Tangier. Known for its rich history and cultural diversity, Ksar el Kebir has become a focal point for both locals and tourists alike.\n\nThe town is steeped in history, with roots dating back to ancient times. Its strategic location made it an important site for trade and military activities. Today, remnants of its past can be seen in the architecture, particularly in the medina, where traditional Moroccan houses feature stunning tile work and intricate wood carvings.\n\nOne of the highlights of Ksar el Kebir is its lively markets, where visitors can experience the hustle and bustle of local life. The souks offer a variety of goods, from colorful textiles and handmade crafts to aromatic spices and fresh produce. It\'s an excellent place to immerse yourself in the local culture and perhaps pick up a unique souvenir.\n\nNature enthusiasts will appreciate the surrounding landscapes, which include lush farmland and rolling hills. The nearby Loukkos River offers opportunities for fishing and picnicking, making it a perfect spot for a relaxing day outdoors.\n\nKsar el Kebir is also known for its warm hospitality. Local restaurants serve delicious Moroccan cuisine, with dishes like couscous and tagine taking center stage. The town\'s vibrant café culture invites visitors to unwind and enjoy a cup of traditional mint tea while watching the world go by.\n\nWith its rich history, bustling markets, and stunning natural surroundings, Ksar el Kebir is a captivating destination that offers a glimpse into the heart of Moroccan culture. Whether exploring its historical sites or enjoying the flavors of local cuisine, Ksar el Kebir promises an unforgettable experience for all who visit.', NULL, 0, 50000, 50000, 200, 4, 'GMT+1', 1),
